A black box in the car?
American road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the falling highway system, and believe to have found the solution in a small black box that takes place in the dashboard of every car.
The equipment that records every kilometer and reports the information to the authorities is at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the planning offices of the states to revise the outdated system for financing US roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly opened up an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Liberators have joined environmental groups and are in favour of the government using the small boxes to record the run-down kilometres - and possibly where they were driven - and then use the information for the calculation of tax documents.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns.
But while one cannot agree on a procedure in Congress, several states no longer wait.
They are currently examining how to switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay for each mile.
Thousands of car drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS surveillance.
This is really a must for our country.
"It is nothing that we will only possibly use," said Hasan Ikhrata, Managing Director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record the hit miles in all California car drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is financed from the taxes paid by the US Americans at the gas column, is broke.
But in America, it's not as much gas as it used to be.
Cars use less gas.
The state oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 cents per litre) has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare, at high prices, to raise the tax even to a cent.
"The gas tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, an expert in traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
"This is the most useful alternative in the long term," he said.
bureaucrats call it a mile-based user result.
It is not surprising that the idea is found in urban liberal terms, for example, the tax could be used to influence driving behaviour in such a way as to reduce congestion and climate-sensitive exhaust gases.
The California planners are relying on the system to develop strategies to achieve the ambitious, legally anchored objectives of the state of climate change.
But the Republican Bill Shuster from Pennsylvania, president of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most common long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also affected by the idea of making drivers pay after the route has been completed.
"This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole," explains Adrian Moore, Vice-President of the Reson Guidelines.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former American transport ministers who, in a report in 2011, asked Congress to move towards miles-based settlement.
The US Senate approved a 90 million-dollar pilot project last year, which would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move and thus responded to the concerns of Members from rural areas who represent people who often have to spend many miles in everyday life on the way to work or to the city.
However, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which currently acquires 5,000 drivers for the country's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the miles instead of the oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering such a thing.
Illinois is testing it with trucks to a limited extent.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, drivers were sceptical about the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
"Concerns against Big Brother and such things were a big problem," explains Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and result management in the Nevada Ministry of Transport.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: "It would be relatively easy to turn the tachograph into an adult surveillance device."
There was no need to build a huge, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology with which the state can capture the run-in kilometres, but not exactly when and where.
In that way, Khan said, the public would also be more calm.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small start-up company called True Milage in California.
The company originally did not start to help state states in the taxation of car drivers.
Rather, their goal was to take a stand in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are to pay on the basis of the run-up miles.
But the devices it tested are also interesting for the road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information that are regularly uploaded by modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Milage.
