Other bodies hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by providing the equipment with more functions than with less.
In New York City, transport officials want to develop a tax system that also allows parking charges to be paid, insurance must only be paid for run-in kilometres, and speed data collected by other vehicles in real time, which allows drivers to avoid congestion.
"Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits that the system offers," it says in a planning document of the city.
Some transport planners, however, wonder whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said that the Congress could simply solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund by increasing the fuel tax.
