Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Far-off planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency now need to agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the next few years.
30 proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Far-off worlds.
More than 1000 planets in other stars have already found astronomers.
No one knows if there's life on some of them at least.
The selection is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or after Earth-like planets, maybe to discover alien life?
These are the questions that the people responsible for the European Space Agency, Esa, are asking themselves.
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are to bring the research to a decisive level.
The budget for such "L-missions" is about one billion euros each.
The start is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas have been discussed, five of which have now come to the close.
A large number of bodies are looking at the proposals, and they are looking at the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee.
In total, the Esa has selected four major questions to which the missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme, launched in 2007, are to find answers.
What are the conditions for the creation of planets and lives?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets that surround these stars - are still in the proverbial dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this dark.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life be created there?
To address this question, the "Cheops" space telescope will be launched in 2017, which will further examine 500 already known planetary systems in our nearby environment.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, the astronomers could represent Earth-like planets and even analyse the composition of their atmospheres and thus look for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is intended to give an idea of the conditions for the creation of life.
An important role is the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation it emanates with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated in an exemplary way.
With the "Solar Orbiter" the Esa has already approved an M-Class mission (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this issue.
The probe is to start in 2017 and monitor the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and his moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the Esa provides the first of the three L-missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme.
The "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is to examine the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The space offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and to examine whether the natural laws we know are still valid there.
It may also be possible to find differences that could lead the physicists to a new theory under which all known natural laws can be united.
How did the universe come about and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos were created by the big bang.
In addition to the common matter, of which stars, planets and living beings like us exist, there is dark matter, the gravity of which holds together galaxies and galaxies, and dark energy, through which the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fraction of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy are made of.
With "Euclid," the Esa has already approved an M-mission, which is scheduled for the start of 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to examine the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the whole sky, allowing conclusions on the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Only two of the 30 proposals will be left at the end of the selection procedure.
In the opinion of many experts, the best chance of a L-mission authorisation has "E-Lisa," a demanding concept for the detection of gravitational waves.
This includes changes in the structure of space time that Albert Einstein had predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, the scientists hope to get behind the project.
The mission provides for a two or three-probe detector to be installed in space.
In contrast to plants on Earth, it could also prove gravitational waves that were created during the big bang, and thus provide new insights on the development of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena," which is to explore black holes, "Icy Planets," another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism," a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder," which is to detect and investigate Earth-like planets.
There are already proposals for the return of samples from Mars, for the research of moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as for solar physics.
