Booming pawnhouses in Singapore, as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawn house in the Bendemee shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga is exchanging a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay the school fees of her daughters.
"My husband and I just bought a house, all my money in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although every month she makes 3,000 Singapore dollars (about EUR 1,730) as an administrative employee and her husband also works, she explains that the monthly family income is not enough.
In fact, demand in parts of South-East Asia - where the debt of households is increasing - is so great that ValueMax, where it has made its exchange, became the third pawn house listed on the Singapurian stock exchange this week.
The pledge of jewelry is not only a fast way to get money - 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga - but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawn houses in Singapore require an effective annual rate of 17 percent, which is just over 15.4 percent that the United Overseas Bank demands, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, the advantage is that there is no need for a review of the creditworthiness or income evidence, which is why loans are possible more quickly than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawnhouses, after families feel the pressure from increasing living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loosening fiscal policy in the developed economies, families with lower and medium-income households are looking for pawnings to compensate for the difference in the stinking economy.
This week, the rating agency identified Standard & Poor's growing budget debt, mainly through increasing mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
The Agency considers that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest budgetary debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economic operators are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has just come out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing export weakness and a decline in consumer demand.
"In the end, this means that, in the face of increasing costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
In the last two years, the historical high levels of gold prices have increased the trend towards the pavement of personal objects, as people take the opportunity to turn the family's jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pawn items are gold in the 200 pawn houses of the city state.
People say, "The gold price looks good, let's get Großmutter's gold chain and get it back next month."
The largest Thai pawnhouse operator, EasyMoney, has experienced a 20% increase in its sales in recent months.
The growth in the pawn business is so strong that ValueMax, the operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to the neighbouring Malaysia - where the company operates four houses - but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is financing this with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it took this week with the Singapore stock exchange.
While some lenders had come into the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yes explains that pawnhouses not only offered more favourable interest rates than other lenders but also did not directly increase the debt.
"Customers claim items that they already own and the liquefied personal items do not increase the budgetary debt," she explains.
The pawnings business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawnings are in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to the ValueMax stores to connect gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they get up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Our customers come to us from every social shift.
"These include well-being who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small companies that have to bridge bottlenecks in the cash flow," says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
