FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft (but do not have phone calls)
From departure to landing, passengers can now hear their electronic devices for reading, working, playing, music and using the image of films, but not by phone, so the new guidelines, which were published by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the USA on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the airline, FAA staff said Michael Huerta at a press conference.
The airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight crew and the rules for the storage of the equipment in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in an announcement.
Currently, passengers need to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not start it again until the plane has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain gives green light.
When entering the landing approach, passengers must turn them off again and must not start again until the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the equipment even at the start, landing and on the rolling field, the FAA stated.
Most of the new transport aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to larger heights for the use of Wi-Fi should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the professional association of professional flight crew members, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regulation is safely implemented - and we are working closely with the airline in this respect - both sides will benefit from it," commented Glading.
We are, to be honest, tired of having to feel like carers on this issue.
However, Internet connections for the surfing, exchange of e-mails, text messages or download of data under three kilometres remained prohibited, the Authority explained.
Passengers are asked to move smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends," the Scrabble-like online game that the actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave a jet of American Airlines publicly because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the airway.
And more heavy devices such as laptops must continue to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Cell phone calls during the flight will continue to be prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may repeal ban on certain electronic devices at start and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board said security experts on CBS News, that mobile phones would still be considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could cause potential interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that the transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission masts," said Rosenker.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to examine this issue, recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years the pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as the democratic senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri believe that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce, because the use of the equipment has become ubiquitous.
In some studies it is said that up to one third of passengers forget or ignore the switch-off of the device.
The FAA began in 1966 to limit the use of electronic devices by passengers after reports of disturbances of navigation and communication equipment by VHF radios carried by passengers, which at that time were the latest technical trend.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA in such a way that they do not care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing passengers with Wi-Fi for a few years when the flight height is reached.
The airplanes adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic devices in accordance with the new guidelines, said Huerta.
Today's electronic devices generally give off much less radio radiation than previous generations.
For example, e-readers only give off minimum radiation when you turn over.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the advocates of easing the restrictions on the use of equipment by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company staff invited a passenger aircraft full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but none were able to find out.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the Passenger Association National Association of Airline Passengers said that he considered the device interference to be real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there were only isolated reports of pilots who spoke for a malfunction of aircraft systems through the equipment, and most of them were very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the switch-off of the equipment by the passengers in the event of an instrument landing under bad visibility.
