On the way through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical assistance to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
You can vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 of the "CNN Heroes of 2013."
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him to be the CNN Hero of the Year.
The winner receives $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his sick father constantly losing consciousness and travelling to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he had only a broken arm, but then an inflammation formed, which spread to his brain and caused a hematoma that was supposed to affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years with his father in crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," comments Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5: 00 in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organisation.
On the other hand, the relationship in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for her, most of the comrades could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and almost three-quarters of the country's health expenditure are private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his countrymen suffer in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team carried out 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organisation called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday he and up to 30 people are forced into small buses and drive on the roof through unfortified terrain to the villages that need help.
It's not always going smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will receive like heroes: a feast, singing and dance and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and wave - with its wide smile and its limitless energy - is happy to attend the happy celebration.
The next morning, the team will start the investigation of hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per drive," said Bwelle.
They come from a 60 km radius around the village - and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document that is necessary for the school but that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, the city hall or an apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operation and the disinfection equipment is fed by the group's generator and thus Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It is an exhausting pensum, but the village musicians usually help to keep the team motivated.
"They are drumming all night, so that we can stay awake and continue our work," says Bwelle.
On Sunday the team will then return to the city, tired, but proud of the work done.
The group - a mixture of Cameroon doctors and foreign medical students - carried out 700 free operations last year and knows that its work makes a huge difference to the people it helps.
A man said that the free operation of a lizard that he had received now allowed him to work again.
"This changes the future of my family," the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works in private clinics in Yaoundé at night.
With this second job he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, said Bwelle; the rest come from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's going to sleep," says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and is a volunteer in Bwelle's group.
He's always in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students such as O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe and support bwelle, this is a chance to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
"We can be in surgery where we help to tap blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle," explains O'Malley.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
The students usually pay for their journey to Cameroon themselves and bring often donated health material.
However, if they are first in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, the transport and the instructions.
"He is no doubt a hero," says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon knows no limits.
For bwelle, the almost permanent work is not a burden.
To help others to live a happier life and thus to fulfill a promise he has given to his father, makes him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this work," says Bwelle.
And I'm thinking of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
