Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants at the top of the park take a look in a dark, 15-metre-deep shaft.
This is the well of the old cathedral, which unfortunately is hardly perceived.
The next station of the tour is the Pretorium, and here the participants rise back down to the depth.
We are here the headquarters of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means is a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for" Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium, "which in good German means as much as" City of Roman Law and City of the Agrippinese, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the Kaiserkulf. "
And the Pretorium is the former Palace of the Governor, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the front room of the exhibition, a tunnel access to the Roman sewage canal, which is preserved here at about 120 meters in length.
"You can walk a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima, if you want," the school will cheer the guests up.
One more surprise, Schulze.
After getting the key at the register, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walk-in shaft.
